==== time ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <ctime>
time_t time( time_t *time );
</source>
}}

The function time() returns the current time, or -1 if there is an error. If the argument ''time'' is given, then the current time is stored in ''time''.

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/asctime|asctime]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/clock|clock]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/ctime|ctime]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/difftime|difftime]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/gmtime|gmtime]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/localtime|localtime]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/mktime|mktime]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/strftime|strftime]]<br>(Other Standard C functions) [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/srand|srand]] - the preprocessor macros __DATE__ and __TIME__

[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==Introduction==
The ''plot'' command plots 2D data linearly to the current axis on the current figure.

==Usage==
Here's how a plot can be created.
<source lang="matlab">
  >> h = figure;                                   % Create new figure and save the handle to h
  >> x = [0:0.001:10];                         % Create x vector
  >> y = sin(x);
  >> plot(x, y)                                      % Plot
  >> title('Sine wave from 0 to 10')        % Set the title of the current axis
  >> ylabel('sin(x)')                              % Set the label for the y-axis
  >> xlabel('x') %set the label for the x-axis
% xlabel('alpha') - - > alpha
% xalbel('\alpha') - -> symbolic alpha
  >> grid on                                         % Turn on the grid
</source>
Graphs can also be created and saved using the command line interface. For example, the following code will create a graph comparing the [[w:en:speedup|speedup]] of two algorithms. The graph created is shown below.
<source lang="matlab">
  >> x = [1 2 4 8];
  >> y = [1 2 1.95 3.79];
  >> z = [1 1.73 2.02 3.84]; 
  >> h = plot(x,y,'--');
  >> hold on; % Plot next graph on same figure
  >> plot(x,z);
  >> hold off;
  >> xlabel('Number of processors');
  >> ylabel('Speedup');
  >> saveas(h,'graph.eps',eps);
</source>

